# CI/CD Principles

## Feedback & Correctness

- Optimize for the shortest possible feedback cycle without reducing confidence.
- Fail fast — run cheap, high-signal checks first (lint, compile, unit tests) before expensive ones (integration, e2e).
- Never sacrifice correctness for speed. A faster pipeline that hides failures is worse than a slow one that catches them.
- Make failures actionable — error messages should point directly to the cause, not require log archaeology.
- Never ignore failures unless they are explicitly documented as non-blocking. Silent failure suppression must be justified and explained.

## Reliability & Reproducibility

- Builds must be deterministic — the same inputs always produce the same outputs.
- Pipelines must be deterministic — given the same inputs, a pipeline must follow the same execution path. Avoid behavior that depends on timing, cache state, or prior run history.
- CI and local environments should behave consistently whenever practical. Differences should be intentional and documented.
- Pin all tool versions (compilers, runtimes, CLI tools, action versions) to prevent silent breakage from upstream changes.
- Keep CI stateless — no state should persist between runs unless explicitly stored as an artifact or cache.
- CI jobs should be idempotent and safe to rerun without unintended side effects.
- CI should tolerate transient infrastructure failures through bounded retries where appropriate, but never hide deterministic failures.

## Efficiency

- Minimize CI execution time and cost — every unnecessary second costs money and slows the team.
- Parallelize independent work — jobs and steps that don't depend on each other must not run sequentially.
- Jobs should declare only the dependencies they actually require. Unnecessary dependency relationships serialize execution and increase wait time.
- Cache everything that is expensive to recreate, while ensuring cache correctness. Never cache outputs whose validity cannot be verified.
- Prefer incremental work — only rebuild and retest what changed.
- Avoid duplicate work — never build or test the same thing twice in the same pipeline run.
- Use immutable artifacts — once built, an artifact must not be modified. Build once, reuse everywhere.
- Every produced artifact should be traceable to the exact source revision, build configuration, and pipeline that created it.
- Validate before expensive work — lightweight checks must gate heavier jobs.
- Skip unnecessary jobs — use conditions and filters to avoid running jobs with no relevant changes.
- Cancel obsolete runs — a new push to a branch should cancel any in-progress run for the same branch.

## Structure & Maintainability

- Keep CI configuration DRY — extract repeated logic into reusable workflows, composite actions, or shared scripts.
- Build, test, and release logic should live in reusable scripts or build tooling, not be duplicated inside CI workflow files. CI workflows should orchestrate, not implement.
- CI commands should be executable locally whenever practical. Prefer `./gradlew test` over workflow-specific logic that can only run in CI.
- Keep pipelines modular — each job should have a single, clear responsibility.
- CI infrastructure is production infrastructure and should be reviewed, tested, versioned, and maintained accordingly.
- Every CI workflow should have a clear owner responsible for maintaining it.
- Prefer automation over manual intervention — any manual step in a pipeline is a bottleneck and a reliability risk.

## Security

- Keep secrets secure — never log secrets, never pass them through environment variables unnecessarily, never expose them in artifacts.
- Apply least privilege permissions — every job and token should have only the permissions it needs. Default to read-only.
- Verify third-party actions and dependencies before use. Pin to a specific version or commit hash; never use floating tags like `latest` or `main`.
- Dependency updates should be reviewed before merging — automated bumps must go through the same review process as code changes. Auto-merge without review is not acceptable.

## Observability

- Make pipelines observable — it must always be clear what ran, what passed, what failed, and why.
- Make logs easy to navigate — use step grouping, clear step names, and summary outputs. Avoid walls of undifferentiated log output.
